metadata.name: (un)existing #244
metadata.description:
The existing nature grows on the unexisting spirits.

Generative sketch, based on the pen and ink drawings of Po Sheng Chen. Po Sheng Chen is an Architect who has drawn nothing but Architecture for over 25 years. He tried to explore something different from his previous style (Brutalism with Magical Realism), so developed his own Minimalist Architecture process and style. After breaking up all the complicated elements and symbols, he chose a simple and naive way to present “pure volumes in the space (the essential of Architecture)”: the Use of different densities of vertical lines to create different faces of volumes, with the addition of horizontal lines to create shadows on the volumes. Shadow determined the form of volumes, then they became a clear composition in the space, Eliminating chaos. These lines seem like spirits to Po Sheng Chen, because they represent the soul of Architecture, but they do not have a specific form or meaning...they are between existing and unexisting! Tezumie is a creative generative artist. He saw the latest experimental drawings of Po Sheng Chen, and after reaching out, the collab was formed with the goal of creating a digital representation of the original concept surrounded by a natural and overgrown environment. The combination of nature and architecture.

Made in p5js.

metadata.name: The Samsara-Verse #58
metadata.description:
Samsara is the endless Wheel of Life, where uncountable numbers of souls ceaselessly wander through its 6 realms - Deva-gati (abode of the gods), Asura-gati (demi-gods), Preta-gati (hungry ghosts), Naraka-gati (Hell), Tiryagyoni-gati (animals), Manusya-gati (the human realm).
 
These realms are interleaved with manifold planes of existence separated by the thinnest of veils.
And yet - these hives of endless activity are but a small fraction of the totality of the metaverse, as multitudes of unformed universes, as yet mere sketches, await their blooming.

This artwork consists of both a visual aspect and a sonic representation echoing the voices of the denizens of the various planes of the Samsara-Verse.

Once the piece has finished drawing, click or press "m" to unmute the soundtrack.
Press "s" to save the image as a ".png" file (4800x3600 pixels).

Collaborative work by Geoffrey Crayon - art design and coding - and Cylonix (JJClark) - sound design. The audio samples used (in addition to generative drones) are from Loopology and Splice.

metadata.name: Raindrops on a Windowpane #17
metadata.description: An impressionistic painting of a windowpane on a rainy day.

metadata.name: Up Above #249
metadata.description:
This piece is inspired by the feeling of insignificance. This feeling, which we all share and feel at some points in our lives is often referred to as negative. But I feel quite the contrary, this feeling is quite beautiful, as it shows small parts together can form something big.

We are but a speck in the universe, like a grain of sand on a beach, like a single drop of water in an ocean, like a single leaf on a tree. But together we are a forest, a river, a sea. Together we are the universe.

Feel free to explore this piece for as long as you want, and feel free to export it in any way you like, and use it for thing like prints, and, of course, I'd love to know about them :)

---

To export your iteration, click the menu bar at the bottom of the screen and press either the "Export current" or "Export custom" button.

metadata.name: FRAG || DEFRAG #38
metadata.description:
FRAG || DEFRAG is structured from the superposition of simple shapes, such as triangles, that alternate in different layers and blending modes. In this scenario, visual complexity is revealed at different times and intensities, offering countless possibilities of perception.

Along with this, the chromatic variation with unique gradations associated with the play of lights and shadows, gives the project different perspectives and depths, in continuous and complementary cycles of fragmentation and defragmentation.

Thus, as in everything that surrounds us, the resulting form does not end in itself, but presents itself as a result of the combination of several other distinct elements.

Nothing is just one thing.

#Main Features
- 13 color schemes “zones”:

* Shadow Sky and Bronze – 12,5% chance
* TIF, Soldier, Zreen and Ice – 10% chance each
* Vascai – 7,5% chance
* Burn Golden, Gray, Lemonade, REC and BR – 5% chance 
* 80’s – 2,5% chance

- 3 canvas formats;
- 3 frequency;
- 2 gradient type;
- 3 degrees of granulometry;

- 1 ultrarare feature | negative effect 

There is only a 1% chance of the negative effect appearing, if you are lucky you will see the following message. "YOU WIN A FREE EDITION OF MY NEXT PROJECT"

Obs.: 
- The first 5 iterations will entitle you to 1 free edition of my next project on FxHash.
- The rendering process should take a few seconds, so enjoy the look of the triangles in action.

July 30, 2022

Generative Token by Morbeck for fxhash.

metadata.name: Magnolia Portrait #175
metadata.description:
Inspired by observation of the incessantly-rooted Pteridophyte and Magnolia, the cognominal series, “Magnolia”, portrays a manifestation of layers of constant streams crossing dynamically in a flow. Through years of growing in fluxed vapor, its knots and roots construct organized and rhythmic patterns within chaotic orders. From two-dimensional layouts to three-dimensional composition, “Magnolia” absorbs its fundamental image, and extend it even further — creating the core of generative artwork.

Press "s" to download

metadata.name: Crash Euphoria #239
metadata.description:
My first foray into shaders and GLSL: This piece experiments with layering many textures guided by an underlying pattern. Each pixel value dictates which pattern is displayed. There are varying levels of imperfections in each pattern, some choose a single color, some use a color guide pattern, some individual strokes decide on another color altogether. These layers are compiled in a shader and warped.

Press 's' in live view to save a png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Ir/rational Beauty #214
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke. www.tribute-hwf.com

"Since the classical age of Greece, the golden ratio has been well known as the most balanced and therefore most aesthetically perfect proportion. In fact, it is supposedly often found in the fine arts and architecture and it is certainly important in geometry. But where is the proof that it is really the most beautiful proportion?

"The computer is proving to be a useful tool in exact art theory. Works of computer art are produced with the help of programs that describe the logic of the construction and its relevant measures. By varying the parameters you can vary the shapes of objects, and on the basis of the reaction of the public you can determine the best option. So it is possible to find valid rules to design works of art.

"A statistical evaluation would be interesting. Please email me with your results for the optimal proportion."

I found it heartwarming that in 2011, Herbert W. Franke wrote the above, accompanied with a simple functional program on a Wolfram Demonstration page (https://demonstrations.wolfram.com/IsTheGoldenRatioReallyTheMostBeautifulProportion/) titled 'Is the Golden Ratio Really the Most Beautiful Proportion?' and invited people to submit their findings to him.

The main idea behind this project is ratios, a variety of them, used in a variety of ways, such as how a rectangle is repeatedly subdivided, or how it influences the aspect ratio of the piece, or how the colors in a palette are selected. These are represented in various styles, some of which are inspired by the aesthetic of Herbert W. Franke's diverse artworks, and his openness to experimentation with new technologies, such as plotter drawings, screens, screenprints, or 2D and 3D digital renderings.

This project, while not designed to be a formal statistical evaluation, is but my fun, colorful, and humble response to your inquiry, dear Herbert.

---

25% of primary sales will be donated on-chain to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke, with the goal of raising 20,000 Euros so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. Any money raised beyond this goal will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.

---

Note: Some mints require WEBGL and/or may take several seconds to fully render.
